<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-03-27T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-03-27T08:00:00-05:00" n="901" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d901">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.24/24: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-03-27T15:00:00+02:00">March 27,
                                    1943—3 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received March 27—12:26 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>590. Department’s 444, March 26, 8 p.m. Having ascertained that Ibn Saud
                            is at or near Riyadh,<note n="61" xml:id="d901fn61">The capital of Saudi
                                Arabia; the King spent only a week or ten days of each year, during
                                the pilgrimage season, at Jidda, location of the diplomatic
                                establishment.</note> I propose to leave for Saudi Arabia via
                            Bahrein within a week’s time provided airplane travel can be arranged.
                                Hare<note n="62" xml:id="d901fn62">Raymond A. Hare, Second Secretary
                                of Legation in Egypt.</note> and Rountree will accompany me.</p>
                        <p>Am gratified that prospects of obtaining irrigation machinery for Saudi
                            Arabia are favorable.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>